  <datafield tag="245" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">A third-order multistep time discretization for a Chebyshev tau spectral method</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="260" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="c">2016-01-01</subfield>
    <subfield code="t">published</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="300" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">8</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">A time discretization scheme based on the third-order backward difference formula has been embedded into a Chebyshev tau spectral method for the Navier–Stokes equations. The time discretization is a variant of the second-order backward scheme proposed by Krasnov et al. (2008) [3] . High-resolution direct numerical simulations of turbulent incompressible channel flow have been performed to compare the backward scheme to the Runge–Kutta scheme proposed by Spalart et al. (1991) [2] . It is shown that the Runge–Kutta scheme leads to a poor convergence of some third-order spatial derivatives in the direct vicinity of the wall, derivatives that represent the diffusion of wall-tangential vorticity. The convergence at the wall is shown to be significantly improved if the backward scheme is applied.</subfield>
